Hi, the newer versions of pymongo have a new gridfs call "get_version" to recover all or specific versions of any given file in "gridfs". This is actually pretty critical if you're using the versioning features of Mongo .. I've had a go at implementing this, seems to work for me, but if we could have a "get_version" call, either this code or something better, that would be great;

```python
@defer.inlineCallbacks
def get_version(self, filename=None, version=-1, **kwargs):
    if version < 0:
        skip = abs(version) 
        self.__files.ensure_index(filter.sort(ASCENDING("filename") + DESCENDING("uploadDate")))
        cursor = yield self.__files.find({"filename": filename}, filter=filter.sort(DESCENDING("uploadDate")),skip=skip,limit=1)
    else:
        self.__files.ensure_index(filter.sort(ASCENDING("filename") + ASCENDING("uploadDate")))
        cursor = yield self.__files.find({"filename": filename}, filter=filter.sort(ASCENDING("uploadDate")),limit=1,skip=skip)
    try:
        defer.returnValue(GridOut(self.__collection, cursor[0]))
    except StopIteration:
        raise NoFile("no version %d for filename %r" % (version, filename))

```

What I really do not understand, why activeColumns is a set instead of vector?
From my understanding now, we can rewrite this function as follows:

```cpp
        static std::vector<UInt> cellsToColumnsSparse(const std::vector<UInt>& activeCells, const UInt cellsPerColumn)
        {
          std::vector<UInt> activeColumns;
          activeColumns.reserve(activeCells.size());
          for (auto it = activeCells.cbegin(); it != activeCells.cend(); ++it) { // loop over the active cells
            UInt col = ((*it) -1) /* as the indices start from 0 */ / cellsPerColumn; /* whole integer division (both must be int, or use floor() */
            activeColumns.push_back(col);
          }
          return activeColumns;
        }
```

What do you think?

* * *

The original function looks like:

```cpp
        static std::vector<UInt> cellsToColumnsSparse(const std::vector<UInt>& activeCells, const UInt cellsPerColumn)
        {
          std::set<UInt> activeColumns;
          for (UInt act : activeCells) { // loop over the active cells
            UInt col = (act -1) /* as the indices start from 0 */ / cellsPerColumn; /* whole integer division (both must be int, or use floor() */
            activeColumns.insert(col);
          }
          vector<UInt> ret{};
          ret.assign(activeColumns.begin(), activeColumns.end());
          return ret;
        }
```

